sec.p:
An important source of systematic errors in two-color microarray experiments is the different properties of the dyes used to label the two samples (Tseng et al., 2001; Yang et al., 2001; Yang et al., 2002) and the hybridization variability from array to array. We used dye-swap design for the same pair of samples in the hybridizations (Table S1) to account for the dye effect (Dabney & Storey, 2007). Background signals were removed from median signal intensity and modelled similarly to Travers et al. (2010) to remove the array and dye effect: \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
